Theory of Computation

Reagan Shirk

August 29, 2019

Theorem

  • The class of regular languages is closed under the \(\cup\) operation. In other words, if \(A_1\) and \(A_2\) are regular languages, then so is \(A_1 \cup A_2\) (same alphabet \(\Sigma\))
  • Proof:
    • Helpful knowledge:
      • Regular language \(L \to\) there is some machine that understands \(L\). There exists a finite automaton \(M\) such that \(L = L(M)\)
      • \(x \in (A \cup B) \iff x \in A \lor x \in B\)
    • Construct a new finite automaton \(M\) that recognizes \(A_1 \cup A_2\) on any input \(w\). Then if either of the two accepts, we accept. Otherwise we reject.
    • We have \(M_1 = (Q_1, \Sigma, \delta_1, q_1, F_1)\) recognizes \(A_1\)
    • We have \(M_2 = (Q_2, \Sigma, \delta_2, q_2, F_2)\)
    • Look at the cartesian product of the states \(Q_1 \times Q_2\), a state \(q \in Q\) is of the form \((r, s)\) where \(r \in Q_1\) and \(s \in Q_2\)
    • Starting state: \(q_o = (q_1, q_2)\)
    • For the machine \(M\) we have \(\delta((r,s), x) = (\delta_1(r, x), \delta_2(s, x))\) where \((r, s)\) is a state in \(Q\) and \(x\) is a symbol in \(\Sigma\)
    • \(F\) for \(M\) is \((F_1 \times Q_2) \cup (Q_1 \times F_2)\)
    • If \(F_1 \times F_2\) useful?
      • I don’t fucking know
      • Ah, it is the intersection rather than the union
      • Proves the intersection theorem

Regular Operators

  • \(\cup\), \(\circ\), \(*\)
  • Can we give the same proof as above for concatenation?
    • I don’t even understand the first proof so I’m not the right person to ask.
  • NFA: nondeterministic finite automaton. May have:
    • multiple arrows leaving from a state with the same symbol
    • not all arrows for some symbols listed
    • many have 0, 1, or more arrows from its state with the symbol \(\lambda\) (the empty string)
  • DFA: deterministic finate automaton can be seen as “parallel computation” with all the different machines running in parallel
    • as a tree of possibilities

How NFAs compute

  • We reach a state with multiple ways to proceed
    • Then the machine “splits” itself and follows each path independently or in parellel
  • We reach a state where no branch corresponds to the symbol that we read
    • the particular copy of the machine dies
  • If any of the copies of the machine are in an accept state at the end of the input
    • the NFA accepts
  • States with a \(\lambda\) on an exiting arrow means the machine “splits” into multiple copies

Example

State Diagram

  • Input: 010110
    • Start at \(q_1\)
    • Read 0, stay in \(q_1\)
    • Read 1, split into \(q_1\) and \(q_2\)
    • With \(\lambda\) split into \(q_3\)
      • Now there are three states running in parallel: \(q_1, q_2. q_3\)
      • \(q_1\) goes to \(q_1\), \(q_2\) goes to \(q_3\), \(q_3\) dies
    • \(q_2\) goes to \(q_4\)
    • Input is accepted because it reaches an accepted state but we keep going because there is more input to be read
    • \(q_1\) gives \(q_1, q_2, q_3\)
    • \(q_2\) dies with 1
    • \(q_3\) goes to \(q_4\)
    • \(q_4\) stays in \(q_4\), the string is accepted

Example

  • Let \(A\) be the language that has all binary strings that have a 1 three positions from the end of the string
    • i.e. 00101 \(\in\) A, 11011 \(\notin\) A
